observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Management to:

Establish internal guidelines or controls on the recognition and utilization of inter-agency fund transfers

Secure copies of Contracts, MOA, or Trust Agreements, and furnish all the concerned offices, such as the CAD for its proper recording, and the Audit Team pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2012-01 and 2009-01;

Reconcile the year-end balances with SAs, update the status of long outstanding/non-moving balances, and facilitate its immediate return, if warranted;

Establish the Admitting and Billing Sections in the VCEH to strengthen internal control over monitoring, recording, and reporting of patients’ information and billings, any issuance relative with the foregoing must be furnished with the Audit Team;

Establish the BAMR Team and facilitate the immediate reconciliation of books between the City and the PHIC pursuant to PhilHealth Circular No. 2023-0028;

Enforce the distribution of the professional fees of HCPs pursuant to PhilHealth Circular No. 0035, s. 2013; and

Require the CAD to effect the necessary adjustments on PHIC claims for fair presentation of the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Re-asses and/or activate the current LCCAP Core Team and its TWG and make the necessary changes/updates, and/or establish a new one, if necessary;


Specifically identify their roles and responsibilities, and ascertain that there would be no overlapping duties with designated personnel; and


Include training or development activities and programs as part of the PPAs for the LCCAP and allocate sufficient budget for such activities.


After the establishment of the Core Team and the appropriate trainings and capacity building of its members, we further recommended that Management:

a.	Conduct the prescribed inventory of GHGs and the current mitigation actions in place, and consider the need for conduct of supplementary vulnerability and adaptation assessment;

b.	Revisit the currently established LCCAP outlined for CYs 2017 to 2030, and make necessary adjustments pursuant to the minimum requirements established in the Circular and supplementing guidelines issued by the DILG;

c.	Establish the prioritization of the identified CC options as mainstreamed or integrated with the City’s development and investment PPAs;

d.	Enhance the succeeding AIP with the appropriate timelines, budget information, and CC tagging as endorsed in the LPIG; and


e.	Organize the Monitoring, Review and Evaluation (MRE) Team, and ensure the implementation of the outlined MRE systems and procedures, both identified in the LCCAP.

We recommended that the City Assessor’s Office:

a.	Conduct regular tax mapping and inspection of all real property (land/land improvements/ machineries) within the City to ensure that all real property units are properly listed in the assessment rolls;


b.	Make representations with the City Register of Deeds to determine, particularly the Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) in that Office, which have no record of Tax Declaration in the City Assessor’s Office for purposes of updating its records and sending of notice of assessment to concerned taxpayers.

The City Mayor and the City Council undertake appropriate actions to effect the reversion of unexpended/excess continuing appropriations totaling P20,372,082.23 to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund which shall be subject for fund allocation in the annual appropriations for the ensuing year through subsequent enactment;

The City Engineer closely monitor the implementation and completion of all construction in progress, especially the four (4) infrastructure projects which remained outstanding and on-going from two to three years, to date; and

The City Development Council innovate/improve the project prioritization process by establishing ranking criteria to assess the urgency and importance of each project with emphasis to inherent risks, time constraints, allocation of resources, and current operational environment.

We strongly recommended the following:

The City General Services Officer to – 

Require the Procurement Office and the Property and Supply Management Office (PSMD) to strictly comply with the compulsory submission of POs within five days from perfection and IARs within 24 hours after the acceptance of deliveries to the Office of the City Auditor pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2009-01 and 
2009-02;

Stop the practice of submitting POs and IARs in batches; otherwise, institute administrative disciplinary action against officials and employees liable thereto, if warranted;

The Procurement Officer and PSMD Officer observe systematic and chronological order in numbering and placing dates in the PO and IAR following the sequence of events and time when the actual purchase and deliveries occurred;

Specifically, for IAR, the PSMD is required to prepare this report simultaneously upon receipt and inspection of consumables/perishable items and within 24 hours submit the IAR to the Office of the City Auditor, prior to the issuance or distribution to the intended end-users/beneficiaries; and

The City Accountant ensure that payments made to suppliers are supported with POs and IARs stamped “Received by” the COA within the prescribed period to ensure compliance with the requirement of COA Circulars Nos. 2009-01 and 2009-02.

We strongly recommended that the City Treasurer and City Accountant exert collaborative efforts to determine the details of composition of prior years’ unremitted withheld taxes, premium contributions, and loan amortizations respectively due to the BIR and Pag-IBIG. Management is enjoined to create an Ad Hoc Committee for this specific undertaking to provide adequate number of personnel for the retrieval of documents pertaining to prior years and to facilitate the reconciliation process with respective fund owners prior to its final settlement.

We also advised the City Treasurer, as the withholding agent and liable officer, confer with the BIR/HMDF officials for the following issues and concerns:

Find ways and means on how to settle prior years’ obligations possibly without available supporting documents on file;

Negotiate/appeal for possible condonation of penalty/surcharge for late remittance of withheld taxes/contributions/loan amortizations;

Bargain for compromise penalty at lower rate or amount in case condonation is not permitted, to be shouldered by responsible withholding agent; and

Resolve the issue on payment of penalty in case the responsible withholding agent in prior years is separated from office by reason of retirement, permanent or total disability, death, permanent departure from the country or other causes.

We recommended that the City Assessor’s Office: 

Conduct regular tax mapping and inspection of all real property (land/land improvements/machineries) within the City to ensure that all real property units are properly listed in the assessment rolls; 

Make representations with the City Register of Deeds to determine, particularly the Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) in that Office, which have no record of Tax Declaration in the City Assessor’s Office for purposes of updating its records and sending of notice of assessment to concerned taxpayers.

We recommended the Management to:
Establish internal guidelines or controls on the recognition and utilization of inter-agency fund transfers;
Secure copies of Contracts, MOA, or Trust Agreements, and furnish all the concerned offices, such as the CAD for its proper recording, and the Audit Team pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2012-01 and 2009-01;
Reconcile the year-end balances with SAs, update the status of long outstanding/non-moving balances, and facilitate its immediate return, if warranted;
Establish the Admitting and Billing Sections in the VCEH to strengthen internal control over monitoring, recording, and reporting of patients’ information and billings, any issuance relative with the foregoing must be furnished with the Audit Team;
Establish the BAMR Team and facilitate the immediate reconciliation of books between the City and the PHIC pursuant to PhilHealth Circular No. 2023-0028;
Enforce the distribution of the professional fees of HCPs pursuant to PhilHealth Circular No. 0035, s. 2013; and
Require the CAD to effect the necessary adjustments on PHIC claims for fair presentation of the affected accounts.

After the establishment of the Core Team and the appropriate trainings and capacity building of its members, we further recommended that Management:
Conduct the prescribed inventory of GHGs and the current mitigation actions in place, and consider the need for conduct of supplementary vulnerability and adaptation assessment;
Revisit the currently established LCCAP outlined for CYs 2017 to 2030, and make necessary adjustments pursuant to the minimum requirements established in the Circular and supplementing guidelines issued by the DILG;
Establish the prioritization of the identified CC options as mainstreamed or integrated with the City’s development and investment PPAs;
Enhance the succeeding AIP with the appropriate timelines, budget information, and CC tagging as endorsed in the LPIG; and
Organize the Monitoring, Review and Evaluation (MRE) Team, and ensure the implementation of the outlined MRE systems and procedures, both identified in the LCCAP.

The City Accountant and City Treasurer undertake appropriate actions to effect the reversion of accounts payable which remained outstanding for more than four years totaling P67,803,374.82 to the unappropriated surplus of their respective funds pursuant to 
Section 98 of PD No.  1445;
The City Accountant verify/review prior years’ records and documents to determine the causes of abnormal debit balances in two subsidiary ledgers for the necessary adjustment and to provide details for the lump sum amount of beginning balances in some of the subsidiary ledgers;
The City Accountant ensure that all unpaid obligations for services rendered during the year are recorded prior to the closing of the books of accounts for fair presentation in the financial statements. The City Accountant, together with the City Treasurer, is advised to communicate with all the contracted service providers of the City requiring them to promptly submit their monthly billings to avoid recurrence of unrecorded liabilities at year end; and
Due to unrecorded liabilities at year-end, the City Accountant is further advised to effect retrospective adjustment to the beginning balance of the Accounts Payable and Government Equity accounts in the ensuing CY 2022.

We strongly recommended the following:
The City General Services Officer to –
Require the Procurement Office and the Property and Supply Management Office (PSMD) to strictly comply with the compulsory submission of POs within 5 days from perfection and IARs within 24 hours after the acceptance of deliveries to the Office of the City Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-01 and 2009-02;
Stop the practice of submitting POs and IARs in batches; otherwise, institute administrative disciplinary action against officials and employees liable thereto, if warranted;
The Procurement Officer and PSMD Officer observe systematic and chronological order in numbering and placing dates in the PO and IAR following the sequence of events and time when the actual purchase and deliveries occurred;
Specifically, for IAR, the PSMD is required to prepare this report simultaneously upon receipt and inspection of consumables/perishable items and within 24 hours submit the IAR to the Office of the City Auditor, prior to the issuance or distribution to the intended end-users/beneficiaries; and
The City Accountant ensure that payments made to suppliers are supported with POs and IARs stamped “Received by” the COA within the prescribed period. This procedure is adopted in other cities and has proven effective measures to comply with the requirement of COA Circulars Nos. 2009-01 and 2009-02.

We recommended that the City Treasurer constantly follow-up the submission of bank credit and debit memos from concerned depository banks, to facilitate the recording of related transactions in the books of accounts. Likewise, ensure that all supporting bank credit and debit memos are attached to the Monthly Bank Statements from the depository banks upon acceptance to avoid      recurrence of unrecorded bank transactions; 

Moreover, we encouraged that Management take immediate action against taxpayers who issue personal checks with insufficient funds and to require the issuance of manager’s checks to make sure that the drawee banks will honor the payment; and 

We also advised Management to officially set a limit in the amount of local taxes to be paid by personal check in order that above the said amount, payments should be settled thru manager’s check or thru other applicable modes of payment.

We recommended that the City Accountant strictly implement the Perpetual Inventory Method of accounting for supplies and materials. Ensure maintenance of complete SLC per commodity/ item to keep track of inventory movement and to facilitate the computation of the weighted average cost on the date of issuance of supplies and materials. In such manner, related expense accounts and inventory accounts will be presented accurately in the financial statements following the prescribed Moving Average Method of costing for supplies and materials; 

We likewise recommended that the City General Services Officer, through the PSMD: 

Maintain complete Stock Card per commodity/stock in the form and format prescribed under MNGAS for LGUs, Vol. II. Fill up the required information to keep track the inventory movement and regularly conduct reconciliation with the balances appearing in the SLC of the CAO; 

Prepare the AIR upon receipt of deliveries and record supplies and materials promptly in their respective Stock Cards. Subsequently submit the AIR to the CAO to facilitate recording in the SLCs; 
Prepare the RIS duly approved by the Head of the Requisitioning Unit. Consolidate the RIS on a weekly basis and prepare the SSMI stating therein the quantity only as the unit cost and total cost will be supplied by the CAO using the Moving Average Method; and 

Receive all deliveries of motor vehicle tires, spare parts, oil and lubricants from the suppliers for proper custody, issuance and recording. Issuance of tires should be supported with inspection/evaluation report duly signed by the authorized mechanic. 

Lastly, we recommended that the OIC-Motorpool Division turn-over the inventory of motor vehicle tires, spare parts, oil and lubricants to the PSMD as authorized custodian under the Local Government Code. However, the Motorpool Division should be allowed to maintain enough supplies and materials for their daily operations.

We recommended that the:

CAO: 

Effect the necessary adjusting entries in the books to reclassify all completed infrastructure projects still recorded under the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts

Compute the corresponding depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation for all completed projects as of December 31, 2020 and adjust the government equity account for the unrecorded accumulated depreciation at year-end;

Provide Construction in Progress Ledger Card for each construction in progress to record the details and payments made to contractors; 

Set-up the liability account for the unpaid costs of completed projects; 

Closely coordinate with the City Engineer to obtain reliable information on all on-going agency asset and public infrastructure projects to ensure completeness of subsidiary ledgers for monitoring purposes, both for the GF and SEF; and 

City Engineer constantly update the City Accountant on the status of accomplishments of on-going agency assets and public infrastructure projects for accurate presentation of related asset, liability, expense and equity accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the City Accountant and City Treasurer: 

Make representations with the GSIS for the reconciliation of their records; 



Create an ad hoc committee that will be responsible for the data gathering and documentation of recorded prior years’ unremitted amount to the GSIS to facilitate the reconciliation process; 

Immediately remit the verified amount of unremitted premium payments and loan amortization to the GSIS, if any, to avoid accumulation of penalty/interest on arrearages. In case the payees could no longer be identified, secure advice from GSIS officials on how to settle the corresponding obligation to the GSIS; and 

City Accountant effect the necessary adjustment/ restatement of liability and equity accounts in the financial statements after reconciliation with the GSIS.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

a.	The Local Chief Executive and the Local Finance Committee coordinate with the City Council for the purpose of formulating strategies to resolve the incurrence of liabilities arising from unpaid just compensation and interest on the four expropriated real estate properties totaling P401,928,272.08 million as of December 31, 2019; 

b.	The City Treasurer intensify the collection of local taxes and identify other potential sources of income to boost their collection efficiency for more funding sources; and

We recommended and the Management agreed to implement the following:

The CAO to update the Real Property Ledger Card (RPLC) of all acquired land and reconcile the SL with the RPCPPE and make necessary adjustments, if warranted; 




The Offices of the City Accountant, City Treasurer, City Assessor, City Legal and the PSMD closely coordinate for the proper recording, valuation and transfer of ownership of all donated land in the name of the City.

We recommended that the City Assessor’s Office: 

Conduct regular tax mapping and inspection of all real property (land/land improvements/machineries) within the City to ensure that all real property units are properly listed in the assessment rolls; 


Make representations with the City Register of Deeds to determine, particularly the Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) in that Office, which have no record of Tax Declaration in the City Assessor’s Office for purposes of updating its records and sending of notice of assessment to concerned taxpayers.

We recommended that the Management require:

The CAO and the PSMD to prepare and maintain SLCs and Stock Cards, respectively;



The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the RPCI and reconcile with the records of the CAO and PSMD;

We recommended and Management agreed that-
The City Mayor/City Administrator make representations with the bank officials to enforce the submission of all bank DM/CMs in previous and current years to facilitate the recording of related bank transactions in the books of accounts. Likewise, require the bank officials to always attach the bank DM/CMs on the Monthly Bank Statement upon submission to the Office of the City Treasurer/Accountant. Otherwise, we advise that management  employ alternative options to resolve this matter to the extent of transferring City’s funds to another AGDB;
The City Accountant and City Treasurer to-
Immediately check the completeness of DM/CMs attached to the bank statements and inform  the concerned bank of any missing DM/CMs;
Record  bank transactions in their respective books of accounts upon receipt of bank DM/CMs; and
Conduct immediate reconciliation of cash in bank balance per GL and Cashbooks to identify the unrecorded transactions for immediate adjustments in their respective books of accounts. Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation to ensure the correctness and completeness of the recorded transactions both in the GL and Cashbooks.

We recommended that:
The Budget Officer ensure adequacy of appropriations for all expenses incurred by the City, including those expenses incurred which 
remained unpaid as of year-end. Initiate appropriate actions to re-align or supplement existing fund, if necessary, to avoid overdraft in appropriations;
The City Accountant prepare the journal entries to record all transactions  incurred  in the current accounting period prior to the finalization of the financial statements, in alignment with the matching principle;
The OIC - General Services Officer immediately furnish the OCA a copy of Inspection and Acceptance Report (IAR) within 24 hours after acceptance of all consumable deliveries and/or soon after the inspection and acceptance by the City personnel concerned; and
The Procurement Officer ensure that there is actual canvass of prices from at least three bona fide suppliers to warrant validity of transactions.

We recommended and the Management agreed to implement the following:

The CAO – 

Make the necessary adjustments to the Land, Other Prepayments and Other Provision accounts for fair presentation in the financial statements;

Update the Real Property Ledger Card (RPLC) of all acquired land and reconcile the SL with the RPCPPE and make necessary adjustments, if warranted; 


The Offices of the City Accountant, City Treasurer, City Assessor, City Legal and the PSMD closely coordinate for the proper recording, valuation and transfer of ownership of all donated land in the name of the City; and


The Management create an Appraisal Committee to appraise the value of donated parcels of land, pursuant to paragraph 47 of the IPSAS 17 for recording in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Management require: 

The City Accountant to establish the RPT and SET Receivables at the beginning of the year based on the RPT Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card as prescribed under Section 20, Volume 1 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs. Likewise, ensure that the setting up of the beginning receivables are supported with a certified list showing the taxpayers’ name and amount due them for proper accounting and monitoring purposes;

The City Treasurer to furnish the City Accountant a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the current year as basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT and SET Receivables, respectively; 

The City Assessor, City Treasurer, City Accountant and the Information Technology Communication Office (ITCO) Head to collaborate intensive efforts in generating accurate/reliable data on RPT and SET Receivable balances by indicating the name of the taxpayers and amount due from them, including penalties thereon; and


The City Legal Officer to institute appropriate civil remedies for the collection of delinquent accounts from RPT and SET totaling P266,609,178.87, including those prior years’ unrecorded receivables that were earlier subjected to legal action for collection.

We recommended that the Management require:

The CAO and the PSMD to prepare and maintain SLCs and Stock Cards, respectively;

The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the RPCI and reconcile with the records of the CAO and PSMD;

The PSMD to prepare the RIS and SSMI to support the adjustment made at year-end in the amount of P758,569,651.17;


The General Services Office (GSO) to–

Undertake adequate planning and monitoring of its procurement to ensure the availability of the needed stocks; and 

Provide a centralized monitoring of the supplies and materials stored in Valenzuela City Emergency Hospital (VCEH) and City Social Welfare Department (CSWD) for reporting and procurement purposes.

We therefore recommended that:
The Management – 

Strictly abide by the restrictions on the granting of transportation allowances and be guided by the Supreme Court (SC) ruling on Aida Domingo v. Commission on Audit (GR 112371, Oct. 7, 1998) and the LBC No. 102;

Cause the immediate refund of the Transportation Allowance received by the OIC with casual appointment in the total amount of P180,000.00 for CYs  2017 to 2018;

The HRMO-Payroll Unit cause the immediate cessation of the TA payments of the City officials who will opt to have GSVs assigned to their respective offices; otherwise, if they elect to continue to receive said allowances, we call for the GSO to take back the assigned GSVs from concerned parties and have them borrow the vehicle/s from the GSO as needed by their office; and

The HRMO-Payroll Unit and GSO provide the City Auditor with the updated list of TA recipients and inventory of GSVs with assigned offices/officials, as well as the certifications that the concerned City Department Heads, Assistant Department Heads and OICs are only availing either TA or GSV.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that:

The CAO –

Record all purchases of supplies and materials related to SEF PPAs under the appropriate inventory accounts upon receipt thereof and record the corresponding issuances/consumptions to related expense accounts; 

Limit the use of the OMOE account only to those expenses which have no specific expense account as prescribed under the Revised Chart of Accounts;
The Local School Board -

Refrain from using the appropriated amount for Education Research Allowance (ERA) in payment of personnel benefits and instead use the same only for valid research related activities as provided in JC No. 1;

Follow the requirements set under Section 52.1 of RA No. 9184 on the use of Shopping as a mode of procurement; and

Henceforth, the City Budget Officer manage the allocation of SEF to provide appropriations for varied expenses of SEF PPAs according to the expense classification prescribed under the Revised Chart of Accounts.

We recommended and the Management agreed to implement the following:
The CAO –
Make the necessary adjustments to the Land, Other Prepayments and Other Provision accounts for fair presentation in the financial statements;
Complete the RPLC of all land acquired and reconcile the SL with the RPCPPE and make necessary adjustments, if warranted;
The Offices of the City Accountant, City Treasurer, City Assessor, City Legal and the Property and Supply Management Division closely coordinate for the proper recording, valuation and transfer of ownership of all donated land in the name of the City; and
The Management create an Appraisal Committee to appraise the value of donated parcels of land, pursuant to paragraph 47 of the IPSAS 17 for recording in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Management require:
The CAO and the PSMD to prepare and maintain SLCs and Stock Cards, respectively;
The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the RPCI and reconcile with the records of the CAO and PSMD;
The PSMD to prepare the RIS and SSMI to support the adjustment made at year-end in the amount of P758,569,651.17;
The General Services Office (GSO) to –
Undertake adequate planning and monitoring of its procurement to ensure the availability of the needed stocks; and
Provide a centralized monitoring of the supplies and materials stored in Valenzuela City Emergency Hospital (VCEH) and City Social Welfare Department (CSWD) for reporting and procurement purposes.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:
The GSO to identify the City officials/end-users of motor vehicles who are liable for the incurrence of penalties totaling P160,224.50 and submit their names, with the corresponding amount of penalty, to the CAO for immediate issuance of billing to recover the amount of penalties advanced by the City. Henceforth, we advised the Management not to accommodate the processing and payment for late registration of motor vehicles at the fault of erring officials/end-users;
The GSO to require all end-users of motor vehicles to submit all the documentary requirements, including the emission test results and stencil of chassis and engines, ahead of the scheduled date of registration to provide ample time for the entire registration procedures. In case of non-compliance, hold the end-users of the service vehicles responsible to register their service vehicles with the LTO at their own personal expense and suspend the supply of gasoline pending registration with the LTO;
The concerned PSMD personnel to promptly report the on-going repair and maintenance of motor vehicles to the LTO on or before the due date for registration to avoid payment of penalty upon renewal of registration; and
The PSMD to make representation with the LTO officials to find ways on how to facilitate the registration of donated motor vehicles which are no longer supported with donation documents and still registered as private vehicle.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Exert effort to locate the documents and verify if the purposes of 
the fund transfers were fully completed and/or discontinued in order to extinguish the liability of the City to the NGAs;
Effect appropriate adjustments to reflect the actual balances of the fund transfers;
Remit/return to the issuing agency the funds transferred to eliminate the dormant balances in the books of accounts; and
Revert to the GF if the details of the fund transfer are no longer traceable.

We therefore recommended that:
The Management –
Strictly abide by the restrictions on the granting of transportation allowances and be guided by the Supreme Court (SC) ruling on Aida Domingo v. Commission on Audit (GR 112371, Oct. 7, 1998) and the LBC No. 102;
Cause the immediate refund of the Transportation Allowance received by the OIC with casual appointment in the total amount of P180,000.00 for CYs  2017 to 2018;
The HRMO-Payroll Unit cause the immediate cessation of the TA payments of the City officials who will opt to have GSVs assigned to their respective offices; otherwise, if they elect to continue to receive said allowances, we call for the GSO to take back the assigned GSVs from concerned parties and have them borrow the vehicle/s from the GSO as needed by their office; and
The HRMO-Payroll Unit and GSO provide the City Auditor with the updated list of TA recipients and inventory of GSVs with assigned offices/officials, as well as the certifications that the concerned City Department Heads, Assistant Department Heads and OICs are only availing either TA or GSV.

